 JDK logger, but I'll keep a note about the `jgroups.log_class` if there's a custom logger involved. The system property confirms using the JDK logger for clarity.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating logger settings**\\n\\nI’m noticing that build tasks don’t set `jgroups.use.jdk_logger`, as they rely on a custom logger instead. The tests, however, set the `use_jdk_logger`, but the LogFactory static initialization might happen before the per-test static initialization.\\n\\nIt seems like, for clarity, having the system property set globally would be better. The existing build only uses the custom logger to exercise the log class. For generic generated tests, I think I should stick with the JDK logger. By the way, there are no docker dependencies required, but I see the existing build includes slf4j-api.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating logging integration**\\n\\nI’m looking at the logging integration and considering adding `org.slf4j:slf4j-api:1.7.31`. But I can test the JDK logger without needing Docker for JGroups. I should use loopback protocols like `SHARED_LOOPBACK`. To test JDBC_PING effectively, it seems I would need a database, so existing mocks could work instead. Moreover, I’ll note that JGroups has optional integrations that aren’t necessary for core coverage. The setup should remain simple, ensuring I can provide pure JSON output.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"JGroups core usage is reachable without extra Maven dependencies or Docker, but meaningful and stable tests should force local loopback/IPv4 networking and avoid optional logging-provider selection.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"Set system properties before creating any JGroups classes or channels: jgroups.bind_addr=127.0.0.1, java.net.preferIPv4Stack=true, and jgroups.use.jdk_logger=true. Prefer in-process stacks such as SHARED_LOOPBACK plus SHARED_LOOPBACK_PING for channel/message coverage instead of UDP multicast or external TCP discovery. If exercising protocol stack creation by XML/name, keep protocols local-only and avoid requiring external JDBC, Kubernetes, DNS, or cloud services.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The resolved JGroups POM has optional logging dependencies such as slf4j/log4j and optional test/integration libraries; generated tests that deliberately exercise those provider paths may need extra dependencies, but they are not required for core coverage.\",\n    \"Network-oriented JGroups tests can be flaky on CI/native-image if they bind to non-loopback interfaces, use multicast, or depend on host IPv6 configuration.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0d55975296dbfa80016a427a4ee0d88195ad928f74ca2b2dd2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3292, "output": 1008, "cacheRead": 35840, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40140, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782741563541, "responseId": "resp_0d55975296dbfa80016a427a3c35a88195a597387eb232f708"}, "toolResults": []}
